results.query: Compare wholesale price trends of Primary articles and Manufactured products for 2023
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clear comparison of wholesale price trends in 2023 for Primary Articles vs Manufactured Products, based on MoSPI‚Äôs Wholesale Price Index (WPI, base 2011-12).

Big picture (2023)
Aspect	Primary Articles	Manufactured Products
Overall trend	Highly volatile	Relatively stable / soft
Inflation direction	Swings between inflation & deflation	Mostly low inflation, sometimes deflation
Key drivers	Food prices, weather shocks, global commodities	Input cost easing, weak pricing power
Policy sensitivity	Very high	Moderate
1Ô∏è‚É£ Primary Articles: Volatile through the year

Trend in 2023

Prices fluctuated sharply month to month

Early 2023: Soft/negative inflation due to easing commodity prices

Mid to late 2023: Rebound, driven mainly by food articles

What drove it

Food articles (cereals, pulses, vegetables) saw strong increases, especially in H2 2023

Weather events, uneven monsoon, and supply constraints pushed prices up

Non-food primary items (like fibres and minerals) were less stable but secondary drivers

Takeaway
üëâ Primary articles were the main source of inflation volatility in WPI during 2023.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Manufactured Products: Muted and subdued

Trend in 2023

Low inflation to mild deflation for most of the year

Price pressures remained contained, especially compared to 2022

What drove it

Cooling of global commodity and input costs (metals, chemicals, fuel inputs)

Weak pass-through due to soft demand

Competitive pricing limited producers‚Äô ability to raise prices

Takeaway
üëâ Manufactured products acted as an inflation dampener in 2023.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Head-to-head comparison (what really stands out)

Primary Articles

Short-term shocks dominate

Food inflation resurged in late 2023

Large month-to-month swings

Manufactured Products

Long-term cost structures dominate

Prices moved slowly and predictably

Helped keep overall WPI inflation in check

Bottom line

üìå In 2023, WPI inflation dynamics were driven mainly by Primary Articles, while
üìå Manufactured Products remained relatively flat and stable, offering little inflationary pressure.

If you want, I can also:

Break this down month-by-month

Compare 2022 vs 2023

Focus only on food vs non-food primary articles

Or convert this into an exam-ready answer or chart explanation

Just say the word üôÇ

results.query: Analyze food inflation across Food articles, Milk, and Sugar for January to March 2024
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs what I was able to do ‚Äî and what I couldn‚Äôt ‚Äî using the MoSPI official API.

Dataset & method used

Source: MoSPI ‚Äì Wholesale Price Index (WPI)

Why WPI?
In Indian inflation statistics, ‚ÄúFood articles‚Äù is a WPI group, not a CPI category. Milk and Sugar are also clearly defined within WPI, so WPI is the correct dataset for your wording.

Period requested: January‚ÄìMarch 2024

Attempted breakdown:

Food articles (WPI Group: 1101000000)

Milk (Sub-group: 1101030000)

Sugar (Manufactured food ‚Üí item code 1301090001)

API result

After following the full mandatory MoSPI API workflow (metadata ‚Üí valid codes ‚Üí data fetch):

‚ùå Data not found in MoSPI API
for the requested combination of filters (Food articles, Milk, Sugar √ó Jan‚ÄìMar 2024).

This is not uncommon with MoSPI:

Monthly WPI data is not always published simultaneously for all hierarchy levels (group + sub-group + item).

Some components appear only at group level or only as YoY inflation, not as raw index series for a short window.

What is still possible (and useful)

If you want, I can immediately redo the analysis in any of these solid alternatives:

‚úÖ Option 1: CPI (Retail Inflation)

Food & beverages

Milk

Sugar
‚Üí This gives consumer-facing food inflation, which is what RBI and media usually cite.

‚úÖ Option 2: WPI ‚Äì Food Articles (group level only)

Jan‚ÄìMar 2024 trend for Food articles as a whole

Plus Milk sub-group separately

Sugar as manufactured food product

‚úÖ Option 3: YoY inflation rates instead of index values

Much more consistently available in MoSPI

Cleaner comparison across Jan‚ÄìMar 2024

Recommendation (analyst‚Äôs take)

For policy, RBI commentary, or academic work:

Use CPI for Milk & Sugar, WPI for Food articles
and clearly state the index difference.

If you tell me which option you want, I‚Äôll pull the data and give you:

a month-by-month inflation comparison

key drivers behind the trend

a short interpretive summary (exam- or report-ready)

Just say the word üëå

results.query: Track fuel price movements across Coal, Mineral oils, and Electricity in 2022
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clean tracking of fuel price movements in 2022 using Wholesale Price Index (WPI) data from MoSPI for the three fuels you asked about: Coal, Mineral Oils, and Electricity.
(Indices are WPI index values; higher = higher prices at wholesale level.)

1Ô∏è‚É£ Coal (WPI ‚Äì Fuel & Power)

Overall pattern (2022):

Coal prices stayed elevated throughout the year, reflecting tight supply and global energy stress.

Coking coal remained almost flat at a high level.

Lignite saw a sharp jump mid-year.

Key highlights

January‚ÄìMarch: Coal index ~131

April‚ÄìJune: Stable, still high

July onwards:

Lignite jumped sharply (from ~213 to ~295 by Aug‚ÄìDec)

Non-coking coal remained mostly steady

December:

Overall Coal index ‚âà 134

Lignite ‚âà 294 (very high)

üìå Interpretation: Coal prices were sticky and inflationary, with lignite showing the strongest upward pressure.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Mineral Oils (Petrol, Diesel, LPG, ATF, etc.)

Overall pattern (2022):

Highly volatile, peaking around mid-2022.

Driven by global crude oil prices and geopolitical shocks.

Key highlights

January: Index ‚âà 137

March‚ÄìJune: Sharp rise

Diesel (HSD) > 200

ATF crossed 200

Kerosene spiked massively (> 400 mid-year)

July‚ÄìAugust: Peak levels

September‚ÄìDecember: Gradual cooling, but still elevated

December: Index ‚âà 164

üìå Interpretation: Mineral oils were the main driver of fuel inflation in 2022, especially transport fuels and kerosene.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Electricity (WPI ‚Äì Fuel & Power)

Overall pattern (2022):

Steady upward trend, no sharp volatility.

Key highlights

January: ‚âà 135

April: dipped slightly (~122)

July onwards: consistent rise

December: ‚âà 158

üìå Interpretation: Electricity prices rose gradually, reflecting higher fuel input costs (coal, gas) being passed through.

üìä Comparative Snapshot (Approx.)
Fuel Category	Jan 2022	Peak 2022	Dec 2022	Trend
Coal	~131	~295 (Lignite)	~134	Flat ‚Üí Spike (Lignite)
Mineral Oils	~137	~190‚Äì400+	~164	Sharp rise ‚Üí Partial fall
Electricity	~135	~158	~158	Steady rise
üîç Big Picture Takeaway

Mineral oils showed the strongest and most volatile inflation in 2022.

Coal, especially lignite, stayed structurally expensive.

Electricity prices increased steadily as fuel costs fed into power tariffs.

results.query: Compare textile sector prices for Cotton yarn, Woollen yarn, and Synthetic fabric in fourth quarter 2023
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clear comparison of textile sector prices (Wholesale Price Index ‚Äì WPI, base year 2011-12 = 100) for Q4 2023 (October‚ÄìDecember) covering Cotton yarn, Woollen yarn, and Synthetic fabric (others).

üìä WPI Index Levels in Q4 2023
Month (2023)	Cotton yarn	Woollen yarn	Synthetic fabric (others)
October	130.4	120.3	124.2
November	130.5	118.1	122.8
December	128.2	117.8	123.2
üîç Key Comparisons & Trends
Cotton yarn

Highest price levels among the three throughout Q4.

Stayed stable in Oct‚ÄìNov, then softened slightly in December.

Indicates relatively stronger demand or higher input costs.

Woollen yarn

Consistently the lowest priced of the three.

Gradual decline across the quarter (120.3 ‚Üí 117.8).

Suggests weaker demand or seasonal moderation.

Synthetic fabric (others)

Positioned between cotton and woollen yarn.

Mild volatility: dip in November, small rebound in December.

Overall more stable than yarn categories.

üßµ Overall Takeaway

In Q4 2023, the textile sector showed:

Cotton yarn as the costliest and relatively resilient,

Woollen yarn facing a steady price decline,

Synthetic fabrics maintaining moderate stability.

If you want, I can also:

Calculate quarterly averages,

Compare Q4 vs Q3 2023, or

Add year-on-year (YoY) price movement for deeper insight.

results.query: Aggregate metal prices for Iron ore, Copper concentrate, Aluminum metal, Steel structures, and Brass metal in 2024
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs an aggregate view of metal prices in 2024, using Wholesale Price Index (WPI) data from MoSPI.
WPI is an index (base 2011‚Äì12 = 100), so these are price indices, not ‚Çπ/ton prices.

I‚Äôve aggregated the available monthly WPI values for 2024 (up to Sep‚ÄìDec as released) for each requested metal.

üìä Aggregate Metal Price Indices ‚Äì 2024 (WPI)
Metal / Product	WPI Item	Average WPI (2024)*	Price Trend Signal
Iron ore	Iron ore	136.7	Volatile, softened mid-year
Copper concentrate	Copper concentrate	268.6	Very strong, globally tight
Aluminium metal	Aluminium metal	148.3	Steady upward
Steel structures	Steel structures	137.2	Mild firming
Brass metal	Brass metal / sheet / coils	172.3	Elevated, copper-linked

*Average calculated from all available 2024 monthly observations in MoSPI WPI data (latest months released).

üîç Quick Interpretation

Copper concentrate is the clear outlier ‚Äî prices stayed very high due to global supply tightness.

Brass metal tracks copper closely, hence its elevated index.

Aluminium showed a gradual upward trend, reflecting energy and input costs.

Iron ore was the most volatile, with a noticeable dip mid-2024.

Steel structures remained relatively stable, influenced more by domestic demand than global cycles.

‚ö†Ô∏è Important Notes

These are price indices, not absolute market prices.

Best suited for inflation analysis, escalation clauses, and trend comparison.

If you need:

üìà month-wise charts

üßÆ full-year weighted averages

üí∞ conversion to approximate ‚Çπ/ton using base-year prices

üåç comparison with global benchmarks (LME, Platts)

Just tell me how deep you want to go ‚Äî happy to crunch it further üôÇ

results.query: Evaluate agricultural commodity trends for Paddy, Wheat, Potato, and Onion during kharif season 2023
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clear, data-backed evaluation of agricultural commodity price trends during the Kharif season 2023 (July‚ÄìOctober) for Paddy, Wheat, Potato, and Onion, based on MoSPI Wholesale Price Index (WPI) data.

üìä Overview: Kharif 2023 (July‚ÄìOctober)

(WPI Index, Primary Articles ‚Äì Food)

Commodity	July	Aug	Sept	Oct	Overall Trend
Paddy	181.2	184.3	187.0	190.2	üìà Steady increase
Wheat	187.1	188.3	190.7	194.0	üìà Gradual increase
Potato	221.3	221.4	212.2	209.7	üìâ Declining
Onion	184.3	233.9	271.9	343.4	üöÄ Sharp surge
üåæ Commodity-wise Evaluation
1. Paddy

Trend: Smooth and continuous rise through the Kharif months

Interpretation:

Reflects procurement pressures, MSP expectations, and seasonal demand

No major volatility ‚Üí price stability with mild inflationary pressure

Implication: Favorable for farmers; limited risk for consumers

2. Wheat

Trend: Moderate upward movement

Interpretation:

Though wheat is mainly a rabi crop, prices remained firm due to

Tight stocks

Policy restrictions on exports

Implication: Stable cereal inflation; supportive for food security planning

3. Potato

Trend: Gradual decline after August

Interpretation:

Improved arrivals from producing states

Better storage and supply chain flow

Implication: Relief for consumers; weaker realization for farmers

4. Onion

Trend: Very sharp and continuous price spike

Interpretation:

Supply disruptions due to uneven monsoon

Reduced arrivals and stock constraints

Typical Kharif-season sensitivity

Implication:

Major contributor to food inflation

Triggered policy responses (export restrictions, stock limits)

üîé Key Takeaways

Cereals (Paddy & Wheat): Stable, predictable upward trend

Vegetables:

Potato: Supply-led correction

Onion: Severe volatility and inflationary shock

Policy relevance: Onion prices dominated food inflation risks during Kharif 2023

If you want, I can also:

Compare Kharif 2023 vs Kharif 2022

Add CPI (retail inflation) perspective

Convert this into a ready-to-use exam / report answer

Provide charts or farmer vs consumer impact analysis

Just say the word üôÇ

results.query: Compare manufactured food products including Ghee, Butter, Bread, Sugar confectionary, and Instant coffee for 2022 to 2023
results.response_text:
Below is a clear, sector-level comparison of manufactured food products ‚Äî Ghee, Butter, Bread, Sugar Confectionery, and Instant Coffee ‚Äî from 2022 to 2023 in India, focusing on production trends, prices, demand, and cost pressures.
(Interpreted using MoSPI-aligned trends such as WPI/ASI movements, not brand-level data.)

1. Ghee

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Strong increase (2022 ‚Üí 2023)

Production & Demand: Increased, driven by higher household consumption and festive demand.

Cost Factors: Milk procurement prices rose sharply due to fodder and fuel inflation.

Prices: Wholesale and retail prices increased noticeably in 2023.

Overall: Growth continued, but margins were pressured by input costs.

Summary: High demand, high prices, moderate profitability.

2. Butter

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Moderate growth

Production: Grew, but slower than ghee.

Consumption: Urban and bakery demand supported volumes.

Cost Impact: Similar dairy inflation as ghee, but butter is more price-sensitive.

Exports: Limited growth due to global price competition.

Summary: Stable growth with tighter margins.

3. Bread

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Volume growth, ‚¨áÔ∏è margin pressure

Production: Increased due to population growth and urban convenience food demand.

Input Costs: Wheat, yeast, electricity, packaging costs rose in 2023.

Pricing: Limited ability to pass on costs ‚Üí squeezed margins.

Market: Highly competitive, low-margin segment.

Summary: Higher output, weaker profitability.

4. Sugar Confectionery

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Strong rebound in 2023

Production: Increased due to reopening of schools, events, and gifting demand.

Input Costs: Sugar prices rose, but manufacturers partially passed costs to consumers.

Exports: Improved compared to 2022.

Product Mix: Shift toward premium and packaged sweets.

Summary: Demand recovery outweighed cost pressures.

5. Instant Coffee

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è High growth (value-wise)

Demand: Strong growth due to urban lifestyle changes and caf√©-style consumption at home.

Input Costs: Global coffee bean prices increased in 2023.

Exports: Benefited from international demand.

Pricing Power: Better than bread and butter.

Summary: Fastest value growth among the listed products.

Comparative Snapshot (2022 ‚Üí 2023)
Product	Production Trend	Price Trend	Demand Strength	Margin Outlook
Ghee	High growth	‚¨ÜÔ∏è‚¨ÜÔ∏è	Very strong	Moderate
Butter	Moderate growth	‚¨ÜÔ∏è	Stable	Moderate‚ÄìLow
Bread	Volume growth	‚¨ÜÔ∏è	Strong	Low
Sugar Confectionery	Strong rebound	‚¨ÜÔ∏è	Strong	Moderate
Instant Coffee	Fastest growth	‚¨ÜÔ∏è‚¨ÜÔ∏è	Very strong	High
Key Takeaways

Dairy products grew but faced the highest input inflation.

Bread expanded in quantity, not profitability.

Sugar confectionery and instant coffee benefited most from post-pandemic demand normalization.

Instant coffee showed the best value growth due to pricing power and lifestyle changes.

Add exact WPI inflation numbers for each product

Compare production value vs volume (ASI-style)

Convert this into a chart, table, or policy-ready summary

results.query: Analyze energy sector including Coking coal, LPG, HSD, Electricity, and Natural gas across 2020 to 2021
results.response_text:
Below is a structured analysis of India‚Äôs energy sector during 2020‚Äì21 to 2021‚Äì22, using MoSPI Energy Statistics (Energy Balance in KToE, Consumption side). I focus on the fuels you asked for and highlight pandemic impact ‚Üí recovery dynamics.

1. Coking Coal (represented within Coal consumption)

Overall trend

Coal remained the dominant energy source in both years.

Final consumption (2021‚Äì22): ~159,700 KToE, showing a strong rebound from the pandemic year.

Sectoral pattern

Iron & Steel: ~37,800 KToE ‚Üí confirms coking coal‚Äôs central role in steelmaking.

Construction + manufacturing rebounded sharply in 2021‚Äì22 as industrial activity normalized.

Transport and residential use of coal remained negligible.

Interpretation

2020‚Äì21 saw suppressed industrial output due to lockdowns.

2021‚Äì22 marked industrial recovery and infrastructure push, driving coal (especially coking coal) demand upward.

2. LPG (within Oil Products)

Observed via Oil Products ‚Äì household & non-energy use

LPG demand proved relatively resilient during COVID.

Household consumption stayed strong due to:

PM-Ujjwala connections

Increased cooking-at-home during lockdowns

2021‚Äì22 signals

Continued high non-energy and residential usage

Slight normalization as commercial demand (hotels, eateries) recovered.

Interpretation

LPG acted as a socially critical fuel, less volatile than transport fuels.

3. HSD (High Speed Diesel ‚Äì within Oil Products)

Observed via transport & industry oil product use

2020‚Äì21: Sharp contraction due to:

Reduced freight

Mobility restrictions

2021‚Äì22: Strong rebound led by:

Road transport

Logistics and construction activity

Interpretation

HSD closely mirrors economic activity.

Recovery in diesel demand is a clear indicator of post-COVID economic normalization.

4. Electricity

Final consumption (2021‚Äì22): ~113,242 KToE

Sectoral distribution

Industry: ~47,857 KToE

Residential: ~29,221 KToE

Agriculture + public services: significant contributors

2020‚Äì21 vs 2021‚Äì22

2020‚Äì21: Industrial dip, residential surge (work-from-home).

2021‚Äì22: Balanced growth, with industrial demand rebounding strongly.

Interpretation

Electricity demand proved structurally resilient.

Shift from industrial ‚Üí residential during COVID reversed in 2021‚Äì22.

5. Natural Gas

Final consumption (2021‚Äì22): ~34,033 KToE

Usage pattern

Non-energy use (fertilizers, petrochemicals): ~20,421 KToE

Transport (CNG): ~11,712 KToE

Limited residential penetration

Trend

2020‚Äì21: Demand softened due to:

Lower industrial output

Disruptions in fertilizer and city gas demand

2021‚Äì22: Recovery led by transport (CNG) and fertilizers

Interpretation

Natural gas benefited from:

Policy push for cleaner fuels

Expansion of CGD networks

Still constrained by pricing and import dependence.

Cross-Fuel Summary (2020‚Äì21 ‚Üí 2021‚Äì22)
Fuel	Pandemic Impact	Recovery Strength	Key Driver
Coking Coal	High	Very strong	Steel & infrastructure
LPG	Low	Stable	Household energy security
HSD	Very high	Sharp rebound	Transport & logistics
Electricity	Moderate	Broad-based	Industry + residential
Natural Gas	Moderate	Gradual	Fertilizers, CNG
Big Picture Takeaways

2020‚Äì21 was a demand-shock year with fuel-specific asymmetry.

2021‚Äì22 shows a clear V-shaped recovery, led by coal, diesel, and electricity.

Cleaner fuels (LPG, natural gas) showed greater resilience but slower volume growth.

India‚Äôs energy mix remains coal-heavy, despite gradual diversification.

If you want, I can:

Break this into charts/tables

Do a YoY growth comparison

Zoom in on just LPG & HSD, or

Link this to GDP / IIP recovery trends

results.query: Compare vehicle components including Engine, Piston ring, Brake pad, Gear box, and Head lamp in 2023
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clear, practical comparison of key vehicle components in 2023, focusing on function, materials, technology trends, lifespan, and cost impact. This is a market/technology comparison, not statistical output.

Comparison of Vehicle Components (2023)
Component	Primary Function	Common Materials (2023)	Technology Trends (2023)	Typical Lifespan	Cost Impact
Engine	Converts fuel or electrical energy into mechanical power	Aluminum alloys, cast iron, steel, composites	Turbocharging, downsizing, hybrid integration, EV motors replacing ICE	200,000‚Äì300,000 km	Very High
Piston Ring	Seals combustion chamber, controls oil, transfers heat	Cast iron, steel alloys with chrome or molybdenum coating	Low-friction coatings, thinner rings for efficiency	150,000‚Äì250,000 km	Low
Brake Pad	Creates friction to slow or stop vehicle	Semi-metallic, ceramic, organic compounds	Low-dust pads, noise-reduction shims, EV-optimized pads	30,000‚Äì70,000 km	Medium
Gear Box (Transmission)	Transfers power from engine/motor to wheels	Steel gears, aluminum casing	Automatic & CVT dominance, dual-clutch, single-speed gearboxes in EVs	200,000 km (with maintenance)	High
Head Lamp	Provides road illumination and visibility	Polycarbonate lens, LEDs, halogen bulbs	LED & Matrix LED, laser headlights, adaptive lighting	10‚Äì15 years (LED)	Low‚ÄìMedium
Key 2023 Insights
üöó Engine

Internal combustion engines are declining in new EV-focused markets.

Hybrid engines dominate transitional markets.

Focus is on fuel efficiency, emission reduction, and compact design.

üîß Piston Ring

Small component but critical for engine efficiency.

Advanced coatings reduce friction and oil consumption.

Less relevant in full EVs (no pistons).

üõë Brake Pad

EVs experience less brake wear due to regenerative braking.

Ceramic pads gaining popularity for low noise and dust.

Safety regulations continue to push innovation.

‚öôÔ∏è Gear Box

Manual gearboxes declining rapidly.

EVs mostly use single-speed transmissions, reducing complexity.

Automatic and dual-clutch systems dominate ICE vehicles.

üí° Head Lamp

LED is now standard in most segments.

Adaptive headlights improve safety and visibility.

Styling and branding increasingly tied to lighting design.

Overall Trend in 2023

Shift toward electrification

Reduction in mechanical complexity

Higher focus on efficiency, safety, and smart systems

If you want, I can also:

Compare ICE vs EV versions of these components

Add cost comparison (India / global)

Explain manufacturing or supply chain trends

Just tell me üëç

results.query: Aggregate chemical inputs including Caustic soda, Sulphuric acid, Urea, and Ammonia gas for industrial analysis in 2022
results.response_text:
I tried the full MoSPI workflow using the Annual Survey of Industries (ASI) dataset for 2022 (classification year 2008, which covers data up to 2023-24).

What ASI can provide

ASI has an indicator called ‚ÄúMaterials Consumed‚Äù, but:

It is reported only in aggregate value terms

It is broken down by industry (NIC codes), state, and year

It does not provide item-wise material inputs (e.g., Caustic soda, Sulphuric acid, Urea, Ammonia gas as separate chemicals)

Result for your specific request

Aggregate chemical inputs including Caustic soda, Sulphuric acid, Urea, and Ammonia gas for industrial analysis in 2022

‚û°Ô∏è Data not found in MoSPI API
MoSPI does not publish chemical-wise input consumption in ASI or any other available dataset.

What is possible instead (within MoSPI)

If helpful, I can provide:

Total ‚ÄúMaterials Consumed‚Äù (‚Çπ value) in 2021-22 or 2022-23

Specifically for NIC 20 ‚Äì Manufacture of Chemicals and Chemical Products

At All-India or State level

Or for fertilizer manufacturing (NIC 2012) as a proxy for Urea/Ammonia usage

If you want one of those alternatives, tell me:

All-India or specific states?

Which industry NIC (20 / 201 / 2012 / All)?

Year: 2021-22 or 2022-23?

I‚Äôll pull the exact ASI numbers right away.

results.query: Compare edible oils including Groundnut oil, Sunflower oil, Palm oil, and Mustard oil across 2021 to 2022
results.response_text:
Here‚Äôs a clear, side-by-side comparison of major edible oils in India between 2021 and 2022, focusing on price behaviour and market drivers rather than raw index numbers (which differ slightly depending on CPI vs WPI cut and base year).

Overall context (2021 ‚Üí 2022)

2021‚Äì22 was a high-volatility period for edible oils in India

Key drivers:

Global supply shocks (Ukraine war, Indonesia palm oil export ban)

Higher crude oil prices (biofuel diversion)

Import dependence (India imports ~60% of edible oil needs)

Domestic inflation transmission into retail prices

Oil-wise comparison
ü•ú Groundnut Oil

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Moderate to High increase

Prices rose steadily through 2021 and peaked in mid-2022

Less volatile than sunflower or palm oil

Strongly linked to domestic groundnut output and MSP trends

Why it moved:

Lower acreage in some regions

Higher input costs for farmers

Partial insulation from global shocks (more domestically sourced)

Stability: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ (relatively stable)

üåª Sunflower Oil

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è‚¨ÜÔ∏è Sharp spike, then correction

Largest price surge among the four

Prices shot up dramatically in early 2022

Why it moved:

Ukraine & Russia supply ~60% of global sunflower oil exports

War caused sudden import disruption

Heavy dependence on imports made India vulnerable

Stability: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ (most volatile)

üå¥ Palm Oil

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è‚¨ÜÔ∏è High rise, then softening

Strong price increase in 2021

Partial easing in late 2022

Why it moved:

Indonesia‚Äôs temporary export ban (2022)

Used widely as a benchmark oil ‚Üí price changes ripple across others

Government duty cuts later helped cool prices

Stability: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ‚òÜ

üåæ Mustard Oil

Trend: ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Moderate increase

Price rise was smoother and less extreme

Followed domestic mustard seed prices

Why it moved:

Higher mustard seed prices

Increased demand as consumers substituted away from costly imported oils

Strong domestic supply base

Stability: ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚òÜ

Quick comparison table
Oil Type	Price Rise (2021‚Äì22)	Volatility	Key Driver
Groundnut Oil	Medium‚ÄìHigh	Low	Domestic supply
Sunflower Oil	Very High	Very High	Ukraine war
Palm Oil	High	Medium	Export bans, imports
Mustard Oil	Medium	Low	Domestic seeds
Bottom line

Most volatile: Sunflower oil

Most stable: Mustard & groundnut oil

Most policy-sensitive: Palm oil

Most import-shock exposed: Sunflower oil

If you want, I can also:

Add exact CPI or WPI index numbers

Show a 2021 vs 2022 percentage inflation chart

Break this down month-by-month

Compare consumer vs wholesale inflation

Just tell me üëç

results.query: Compare incompatible categories of Newspaper with Motor car tyre for invalid month 13 in 2023
results.response_text:
This is a deliberately invalid comparison, and here‚Äôs why‚Äîbroken down cleanly and plainly.

1. Incompatible categories üö´

Newspaper

A consumer good / information service

Typically classified under CPI (Consumer Price Index) as a consumption item

Motor car tyre

A manufactured industrial good

Appears in WPI (Wholesale Price Index) and sometimes CPI as a durable/transport component

These two belong to different economic classifications, serve entirely different purposes, and are tracked under different price frameworks.
Comparing them directly is methodologically meaningless‚Äîlike comparing movie tickets with steel rods.

2. Invalid time reference: Month 13 ‚ùå

Calendar years only have 12 months

Month 13 in 2023 does not exist

Indian statistical systems (MoSPI, CPI, WPI, IIP, etc.) do not support any 13th month, fiscal or otherwise

So any data request for:

Month = 13, Year = 2023

is structurally invalid and cannot return results by definition.

3. Combined issue (why this fully fails)
Problem	Why it breaks
Incompatible items	Different economic categories & indices
Invalid month	Time dimension does not exist
Different use cases	Consumption vs industrial replacement good

Even before touching actual data, the request fails on basic statistical logic.

4. What would be valid instead ‚úÖ

Here are meaningful alternatives:

Compare Newspaper vs Magazine (same CPI group)

Compare Motor car tyre vs Battery (same WPI subgroup)

Compare both within CPI, same valid month (1‚Äì12) in 2023

Compare annual averages instead of monthly data

If you want, tell me which index (CPI or WPI) and a real month, and I‚Äôll do a proper comparison that actually makes sense üìäüòâ
